                    <lb n="1"/>vāmaḥ
                    <lb n="2"/>parā<choice><sic>bh</sic><corr>p</corr></choice>araḥ
                </p>
                </div>
            
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app loc="2">
                        <lem>parābharaḥ</lem>
                        <note>Read <foreign>parāparaḥ</foreign> (see the Kāñchī inscriptions) or <foreign>parāvaraḥ</foreign> (<ref target="DHARMA_INSSIIv01p0i0016">No. 16</ref>). The softening of a single consonant between two vowels in <foreign>parābhara</foreign>, <foreign>pridhivi</foreign> (<ref target="DHARMA_INSSIIv01p0i0002">No. 2</ref>) and <foreign>ubhāya</foreign> (<ref target="DHARMA_INSSIIv01p0i0005">No. 5</ref>) is evidently due to the influence of the Tamil vernacular on the pronunciation of Sanskrit words.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            
            <div type="translation" source="bib:Hultzsch1890_01">
                <p>Vāma (<hi rend="italic">the handsome</hi>). Parāpara (<hi rend="italic">the omnipotent</hi>).</p>
                
            </div>
            
            <div type="commentary">
